<HEADLINE>
<P>
BURBANK HATCHET JOB? 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Residents of Burbank's Rancho area said a private tree-trimming company hired 
by the city butchered neighborhood trees to make room for a power line. 
</P>
<P>
Trees were cut into flat-top and V-shaped forms, Burbank electric services 
manager Greg Simay said. Most of the trimmed trees are along a four-block 
stretch of Parkside Avenue, with some trees along Mariposa Street and 
Morningside Drive also cut. 
</P>
<P>
Simay said two people have complained to the city about the trimming. In 
response, City Councilman Michael Hastings has proposed that the city review 
its tree-trimming policy. 
</P>
<P>
"It's not so much that the job needs to be done, it's how it's being done," 
said Jim Vorhees, a Mariposa Street resident who also is a member of the 
Burbank Civic Pride Committee. "It's just a hatchet job." 
</P>
<P>
The trimming was needed to create a five-foot clearance for a 4,000-volt power 
line along Parkside Avenue, Simay said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
