<HEADLINE>
<P>
POP MUSIC REVIEW; 
</P>
<P>
ROD STEWART AT HOLLYWOOD BOWL -- WITH CONVICTION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DENNIS HUNT, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
What's gotten into Rod Stewart? 
</P>
<P>
He's actually singing these days instead of shouting. What's more, he even 
seems to care about what he's singing. 
</P>
<P>
His sold-out show at Hollywood Bowl on Monday night was one of his best in 
recent years. Right now, the gravel-voiced singer, backed as usual by an 
excellent band, has one of the liveliest shows in rock. 
</P>
<P>
His most recent album, the year-old, 2-million-selling "Out of Order," has not 
only rejuvenated his sagging career, it seems to have rejuvenated him too. 
</P>
<P>
Stewart's shows this decade have mostly been all frolicking and little serious 
singing. Fun's fun, but his casual attitude was getting to be a bit much. He'd 
sing off-key or blow lyrics and didn't seem to care. 
</P>
<P>
A few years ago, Stewart seemed like an over-the-hill rocker having his last 
fling. In those days, when he sang ballads such as Otis Redding's "Dock of the 
Bay" and "Try a Little Tenderness," he appeared to be resting up from his 
relentless, pointless prancing. But at the Bowl, he put some feeling into those 
songs. You felt his conviction -- his genuine effort to interpret the lyrics. 
</P>
<P>
These days, he's striking a balance between rollicking rowdiness and vocalizing 
with conviction. On Monday, he very carefully sang the material from his 
current album and had rip-roaring fun with oldies such as "Twistin' the Night 
Away," "Every Picture Tells a Story" and "Hot Legs" -- songs that he can by now 
sing with a minimum of effort. 
</P>
<P>
Stewart still does some of his signature preening, prancing and fanny-wiggling 
-- but not nearly as much as he used to. Maybe he thinks it's too undignified 
for a 44-year-old man to spend a whole show cavorting like a Chippendale's 
dancer. 
</P>
<P>
When he did some leaping and prancing (he's amazingly limber for an old-timer), 
it seemed to have more of a purpose. Maybe he just wanted to show that he can 
still do it -- that's he's one rocker who's not yet ready for the rocking 
chair. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Concert Review 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA080289-0065 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 89793 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
August 2, 1989, Wednesday, Home Edition 
</P>
